Written August 10, 2016
Bkk10110
10 contributions
Small museum but with excellent exhibits
Jul 2016 • Couples
A wonderful collection of artifacts, some truly beautiful, from an often overlooked civilization. If you like Southeast Asian works of art, you will enjoy and appreciate the exhibit. It shows clear influences from Khmer and Javanese art, while at the same time being different and unique. In my neophyte view, more graceful and playful than either.
There are 4 main exhibit rooms/areas covering the 4 main sites/periods of Cham civilization. Think it is best to go (somewhat) chronologically from the MS, DD, TK and TM sites. (These are abbreviations for the real name of the sites which I would probably misspell. If you go, you will understand.)
Don't understand at all why there are a fair number of negative reviews of the museum on trip advisor. Yes it is small. Yes it can get warm. But again if you like this kind of thing it is well worth putting up with these minor inconveniences. And if you don't, then not worth going anyway to begin with.
Audio guides are well worth the 1 USD. Takes just about an hour for the whole thing.
Most annoying thing about the museum? Visitors taking photos of themselves with their hands and arms on the exhibits. Don't understand what part of "DO NOT TOUCH" these people do not understand. One kid was about to literally sit (!) on an exhibit for a photo before I played Grumpy Scrooge and shooed her away.
Sobering too. You see the whole rise and fall of a civilization that once flourished for about 7 odd centuries. Highlights of what they left behind now only fill a few rooms in a small museum. From what I heard, there are supposed to be only around 15,000 Cham left in Vietnam nowadays.
Written July 20, 2016
Pulkita
Noida, India831 contributions
Indian origins
Feb 2016 • Couples
I'm indian. It was wonderful to find out how much these sculptures resonated indian history culture and mythology. It was exciting to see how art has travelled so far and still all the beliefs were intact. Ofcourse the chams were of Indian origin. I could've spent another hour there easily.
I also enjoyed their display method and the information displays. There were placards and u could carry them around as u walk about the gallery. It explains about several sculptures. When you're done with one gallery you leave the placard back in place for someone else and pick up another placard for the next gallery. That way you are not jamming the walls with info displays. Plus people don't have to huddle around one display to see what's written. You can stand at your own distance and observe for as long as you like without people having to push their way around you to get past. Its got a good collection of the cham sculptures.
Often people don't like/appreciate this museum and I feel it's because of their lack of understanding for Indian mythology and the connection these sculptures have with it.
It was wonderful to have visited statues of Indian God's such as shiva and parvati while in danang.
Parking is available behind the museum. Entrance from the main road/signal/crossroad.
Theres a museum shop which has few collectibles if you'd like.
Written July 5, 2016
